You visited the Nobel Library yesterday.

26:24.819 --> 26:25.980
Yesterday, yes.

26:26.080 --> 26:27.962
So you would have seen the shelves.

26:28.002 --> 26:29.524
That's right, yeah.

26:30.044 --> 26:31.926
with inspiration from Schokloster.

26:32.006 --> 26:33.387
Yes, that's exactly right.

26:33.407 --> 26:33.608
Yeah.

26:33.628 --> 26:34.689
In the 60s?

26:34.849 --> 26:35.309
Oh, yes.

26:35.329 --> 26:39.414
Yes, that's right.

26:39.454 --> 26:43.037
Tell me, tell me who, how you get to have so many books here.

26:44.018 --> 26:45.079
How did this happen?

26:45.880 --> 26:47.582
It started with Korgoster Rangen.

26:48.262 --> 26:52.126
And in 1665, he made the catalog.

26:53.268 --> 26:58.633
And about that time, those rooms were ready.

26:58.968 --> 27:05.076
So he started to put his books in the biggest rooms in this department.

27:05.096 --> 27:08.962
It's a room called Rome.

27:08.982 --> 27:14.369
And this collection was his lifetime less than 2,000 volumes.

27:14.389 --> 27:17.794
But when he died, he had about 2,400 volumes.

27:18.255 --> 27:19.636
Which is considerable for the time.

27:19.717 --> 27:20.818
Yes, yes it is.

27:22.000 --> 27:25.144
And now only...

27:26.018 --> 27:27.880
a part of that collection is kept here.

27:27.900 --> 27:34.908
Because when he died, his collection was divided into four parts for his daughter.

27:34.928 --> 27:40.255
And only the part that belonged to the daughter who inherited the castle is still kept here.

27:40.956 --> 27:41.837
That's a pity.

27:41.857 --> 27:51.027
But his daughter was married to Count Breuer, and Count Breuer took his books here from another castle, Rilberholm, that's north of Stockholm.

27:51.528 --> 27:54.051
And he also had a collection in Stockholm, and he took

27:54.402 --> 27:55.884
that collection here too.

27:56.465 --> 28:01.773
And then he inherited a collection from an island in the south of Sweden, Die Stingsöl.

28:03.055 --> 28:13.069
That was the collection of his relative of... Uncle Brøy, yes.

28:13.971 --> 28:18.597
So at the beginning of the 18th century there were actually three family collections here.

28:20.360 --> 28:23.785
And in the middle of the 18th century

28:24.608 --> 28:33.536
A collection from a castle north of Uppsala that belonged to the Bjelke family came here.

28:33.576 --> 28:36.579
How were they coming here?

28:37.080 --> 28:38.841
Heritage.

28:38.941 --> 28:41.063
So this is really a lot of different libraries.

28:41.203 --> 28:42.865
Yes, there are five different libraries.

28:43.145 --> 28:44.867
That's in the material you gave me?

28:44.927 --> 28:47.970
Yes, yes it is.

28:47.990 --> 28:53.755
And the collection from Salsa, the collection coming here in the middle of the 18th century, that's the biggest collection.

28:54.393 --> 28:55.835
with 8,000 volumes.

28:55.855 --> 28:58.299
So you have a total of how many books approximately?

28:58.439 --> 29:13.180
Totally 20,000 volumes, but some of those volumes have got those small prints made for weddings and for funerals, or maybe only four or eight sides, and they are collected in volumes.

29:13.200 --> 29:21.152
So we could talk about 20,000 volumes and about 30,000 prints.

29:21.172 --> 29:21.312
Mm-hmm.

29:24.211 --> 29:29.757
And in terms of the library itself, what kinds of books are they?

29:29.777 --> 29:30.759
Are they important books?

29:30.859 --> 29:34.183
Are they of great interest as scholars, and why?

29:34.203 --> 29:37.186
What is here that you are unlikely to find someplace else?

29:37.206 --> 29:38.167
Oh, yes, yes.

29:38.247 --> 29:44.094
If I start with Carl Gustav Rangen, there are lots of books that he was supposed to have.

29:44.134 --> 29:47.959
That belonged to a man of his position.

29:48.820 --> 29:52.564
But there are also many books that we really know that he was interested of.

29:53.320 --> 29:54.943
to have, to read, to study.

29:54.964 --> 29:57.329
So he was an intellectual, you would say?

29:58.110 --> 29:58.611
In a way.

29:58.711 --> 30:02.940
I'm going to be very careful now.

30:03.522 --> 30:08.492
Because he was very interested in architecture and in science.

30:09.875 --> 30:13.523
And he bought new books on those items.

30:14.397 --> 30:15.118
All his life.

30:15.378 --> 30:19.082
And where did he buy his books, given that period when he lived?

30:19.122 --> 30:24.028
Yes, that was from about 1640, until he died.

30:24.488 --> 30:25.609
So where did he buy his books?

30:25.630 --> 30:26.350
Book agent.

30:26.370 --> 30:27.331
Who was his book agent?

30:27.351 --> 30:29.634
Yes, he had lots of book agents, you see.

30:29.654 --> 30:34.439
He had agents in Hamburg, in Frankfurt, in Amsterdam, and even in London.

30:35.160 --> 30:36.782
But he bought very few books from London.

30:37.062 --> 30:38.584
But he didn't write any books, no?

30:38.604 --> 30:40.866
No, no.

30:40.886 --> 30:42.568
Frankfurt, Amsterdam, where else?

30:42.588 --> 30:44.050
Amsterdam, Nynberg.

30:44.165 --> 30:46.287
Uh-huh.

30:46.308 --> 30:50.212
And so they're largely in, they're almost all mostly in Latin, the books?

30:50.272 --> 30:54.617
Yes, but actually Havre Favanger preferred books in modern languages.

30:55.198 --> 30:55.338
Uh-huh.

30:55.358 --> 31:01.245
So if it was possible to get a book in German or French, they prefer that to Latin.

31:01.265 --> 31:01.405
Uh-huh.

31:01.425 --> 31:12.578
And that's quite remarkable because Pagot, Pagot, because the account from his time and his language, he always bought books in Latin.

31:13.019 --> 31:13.159
Uh-huh.

31:13.662 --> 31:16.065
Did he buy books for content, or are there any rare books?

31:16.085 --> 31:18.267
Are there any incunables here, for instance?

31:18.527 --> 31:22.511
Yes, there are incunables, and most of them were taken as war booties.

31:23.412 --> 31:24.253
By whom?

31:24.273 --> 31:24.694
By Rangel.

31:25.635 --> 31:29.599
He took a war bootie in Germany, in Poland, and also in Denmark.

31:29.619 --> 31:30.780
And they're here, they're here.

31:31.060 --> 31:35.826
And they are here, yes, they are here.

31:35.846 --> 31:37.728
Will you show some together with the ink text?

31:37.948 --> 31:38.168
Sure, yeah.

